The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | In the City
                                                                                                               IN THE CITY
                  
	 Second seed and world under-16 boys champion B. Adhiban of Petroleum Sports Board triumphed in the war of nerves to win the National Challenger Chess Championship at Town Hall on Monday.      
	Overnight leaders  Mary Ann Gomes of Bengal and B. Adhiban  played each other in the final round, requiring to win to be the clear champion. Adhiban kept his cool to emerge winner with 10.5 points when Mary Anns French defence proved insufficient to hold him. Himanshu Sharma of Haryana finished second, while Deep Sengupta finished third.          
	 Sports minister M.S. Gill has invited former India captain Badru (Samar) Banerjee to the National Sports Day function on August 29, to be held in the capital.                                                                                                                                                                        
